    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1878-09-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1878-09-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="323"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                <head>No. 318.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bingham</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Evarts</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tokei, Japan</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1878-09-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 13, 1878</date>. (Received October
                        18.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 858.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Refering further to my dispatch No. 796, in
                    relation to the assassination of his excellency Mr. Okubo, it gives me pleasure
                    to note that on the hundredth day after the death of that faithful minister it
                    pleased the imperial household of His Majesty the Emperor to present to the
                    family of the deceased 30,000 yen, as appears by a notice published in the Nichi
                    Nichi Shimbun, a paper issued in this capital. I inclose a translation of the
                    notice.</p>
                <p>According to custom in Japan, the hundredth day after the death of a friend is
                    often observed in memory of the deceased.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JNO. A. BINGHAM.</signed>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Inclosure in No. 858.]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Translation from the Nichi Nichi Shimbun, August
                            31, 1878.]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <p>The 21st instant (August) being the hundredth day since the assassination of
                        the late Udaijin (junior prime minister, posthumous title given to Mr.
                        Okubo), Mr. Okubo, his family were presented with a gift of 30,000 yen from
                        the imperial household department.</p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
